There is a specific case where this fails. Here's the code;
            if "AWS_CREDENTIAL_FILE" in os.environ:
                full_path = expanduser(os.environ['AWS_CREDENTIAL_FILE'])
                try:
                    self.load_credential_file(full_path)
                except IOError:
                    warnings.warn('Unable to load AWS_CREDENTIAL_FILE (%s)' % full_path)

If the AWS_CREDENTIAL_FILE is defined, it is expected to be valid. If it isn't defined, this block is skipped. I find this annoying since I don't need this for the proxy, but it is part of the general configuration package in boto.

This is what I tried before, but I just played with where it was implemented and I can get it to work this time. I had to do;

import os
if 'AWS_CREDENTIAL_FILE' in os.environ:
    del os.environ['AWS_CREDENTIAL_FILE']

before anything in the initial file the console loads (euca-console-server). Any later and the python pyami/config.py gets loaded and the Config initializer gets called (looking for this environment variable).

I'll comment and leave this in there!

This can be tested by doing something like;
export AWS_CREDENTIAL_FILE=blargh
./launcher.sh

That way, the variable is set to something invalid. If you don't see this message right away, it's fixed;
/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/2.7/lib/python2.7/site-packages/boto-2.9.6-py2.7.egg/boto/pyami/config.py:77: UserWarning: Unable to load AWS_CREDENTIAL_FILE (blargh)
  warnings.warn('Unable to load AWS_CREDENTIAL_FILE (%s)' % full_path)
